  </table>

  <h2>Security</h2>
  <p>All connection credentials are <strong>encrypted at rest</strong> using Fernet symmetric encryption before being stored in the database. Credentials are only decrypted in memory when a run is executed.</p>

  <h3>Example</h3>
  <pre><code set:html={`Connection: "Production Postgres"
Type: postgres
Config:
  host: db.example.com
  port: 5432
  database: production
  username: readonly_user
  password: ••••••••`} /></pre>

  <h2>How to add a connection</h2>
  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2">
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Connections</strong> in the sidebar</li>
    <li>Click <strong>New Connection</strong></li>
    <li>Enter a descriptive name (e.g., "Production Postgres")</li>
    <li>Select the connection type from the dropdown (e.g., <code>postgres</code>, <code>bigquery</code>, <code>s3</code>)</li>
    <li>Fill in the required fields — host, port, database, credentials, etc. Fields change based on the selected type</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Test Connection</strong> to verify credentials are correct</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create Connection</strong> to save</li>
  </ol>
  <p>You can also toggle <strong>Use raw JSON config</strong> to paste connection credentials as a JSON object directly.</p>

  <h2>Source Freshness</h2>
  <p>You can configure freshness checks on source connections to monitor whether data is arriving on time. This uses dbt's source freshness feature.</p>
  <pre><code set:html={`Freshness Config:
  loaded_at_field: updated_at
  warn_after: 12 hours
  error_after: 24 hours`} /></pre>
</DocsLayout>
